{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"47622047-1810-4269-b83c-d45977d704d4","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` only affects **iOS** safe area insets. You're likely still seeing gaps on **Android** because the app isn't drawing behind system bars. You need to address both platforms:\n\n**iOS** — in your XAML page header, add:\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\nios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n```\n\n**Android** — enable edge-to-edge in `MainActivity.cs`:\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    if (Window != null)\n    {\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n        Window.StatusBarColor = Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent;\n        Window.NavigationBarColor = Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nYou'll need these Android usings:\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n```\n\n> **Note:** On .NET 10 targeting Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` is still needed to tell the layout system not to inset your content away from the bars.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7ef36380-1d51-4eb6-824c-0abfbff39b55","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI full-screen/edge-to-edge display. This is a common issue where setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone isn't sufficient. Let me provide the answer from my knowledge.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind the system bars (status bar and navigation bar), you need to do more than just set safe area edges. The key steps are:\n\n1. On **Android**, you need to enable edge-to-edge mode. In .NET 10 / Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but for older versions you may need to call `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` or use the new `Window.EdgeToEdge` API.\n\n\n2. On **iOS**, you'll want to use `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the specific view or set `UseSafeArea` to false via the iOS-specific API to ensure content truly extends to the edges.\n\nFor **Android**, the challenge is different—content doesn't automatically render behind system bars, so you need to handle window insets properly to achieve that edge-to-edge effect.\n\nThe core fix in MAUI comes down to disabling safe area constraints on iOS and managing inset handling on Android. I should check what's available in the latest .NET MAUI for proper edge-to-edge support. On iOS, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` handles the safe area, but Android requires separate configuration through the MainActivity or Window handler to extend content behind system bars. The user is likely missing the Android-specific setup since `SafeAreaEdges` is primarily an iOS concept.","outputTokens":1229,"requestId":"E837:152429:275AF57:2B87443:69F942E6"},"id":"33b14818-bb80-4df1-b1ba-71c133488f69","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:08:16.990Z","parentId":"b6749991-b435-46d8-b1b9-0adedd201cb8"}
